The rule comes from discord server discussion.

```
language js(typescript,jsx)

// First check if this file imports createFileRoute from @tanstack/react-router
`$program` where {
  // Check for the specific import
  $program <: contains or {
    `import { $imports } from "@tanstack/react-router"` where {
      $imports <: contains `createFileRoute`
    },
    `import $imports from "@tanstack/react-router"` where {
      $imports <: `createFileRoute`
    }
  },
  // If import exists, find components with a single traversal
  $program <: contains or {
    // Function declaration components
    `function $ComponentName($props) {
      $body
    }` where {
      $ComponentName <: r"^[A-Z][a-zA-Z0-9]*$",
      register_diagnostic(span=$ComponentName, message=`Component "<$ComponentName />" should not be defined in a route file`, severity="error")
    },
    // Arrow function components
    `const $ComponentName = ($props) => {
      $body
    }` where {
      $ComponentName <: r"^[A-Z][a-zA-Z0-9]*$",
      register_diagnostic(span=$ComponentName, message=`Component "${$ComponentName}" should not be defined in a route file`, severity="error")
    },
    // Default exported components (combined into one pattern)
    `export default function $ComponentName($props) {
      $body
    }` where {
      register_diagnostic(span=$ComponentName, message="Default exported components should not be defined in route files", severity="error")
    },
    `export default ($props) => {
      $body
    }` where {
      register_diagnostic(span=$props, message="Default exported arrow functions should not be defined in route files", severity="error")
    }
  }
}
```

this rule is indeed very slow. I noticed that the `$program` is a match all pattern. So it is possible that the rule runs on every ast node. to make thing worse, the `contains` shall check every children nodes as well so the rule is `O(n^2)`. 

I ran this rule on vscode repo and it took 70s with biome v2 (without it biome runs sub 2s). but i wrote an equivalent rule with ast-grep it runs only 0.5s (with slower tree-sitter parser)

[playground link](https://ast-grep.github.io/playground.html#) for auditing to ensure it is an apple-to-apple comparison


The trick in ast-grep is that it will filter ast-node by the pattern's AST type. So it will not have quadratic perf issue. https://github.com/ast-grep/ast-grep/blob/61f5c13292b38a81c73978c3a408390160ad6b92/crates/config/src/rule_core.rs#L218-L228

Hope biome can also have this optimization!

